        <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Dog Training Activities & Tips</h2>

        <!-- Basic Comands and leash training-->
        <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Basic Commands</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Start with essential commands like “sit,” “stay,” “come,” and “down.” These lay the foundation
                        for good behavior and safety.</li>
                    <li>Use treats and praise to reinforce positive behavior, keeping sessions short and engaging.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/sit.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Leash Training</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Practice leash walking to teach your dog not to pull and to stay close by your side.</li>
                    <li>Reward them whenever they follow your lead and maintain a relaxed leash.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/lead.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="lead training">
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Recall Training and Impulse Control-->
        <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Recall Training (Come When Called)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Practice recall by calling your dog back to you during playtime. Start in an enclosed space and
                        use treats as a reward.</li>
                    <li>Gradually increase the distance and introduce distractions to build reliability.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/recall.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Reacall Commands">
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Impulse Control Games</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use commands like “wait” or “leave it” to teach self-control. This is particularly helpful in
                        situations with food or exciting stimuli.</li>
                    <li>Reward your dog only when they follow your instructions, reinforcing patience and focus.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/impulse.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Impulse Commands">
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Additional Training Activities -->
        <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Interactive Toys & Puzzles</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Introduce puzzle toys and treat dispensers to keep your dog mentally stimulated.</li>
                    <li>Rotate toys to keep them interesting, as mental challenges help reduce boredom and promote
                        problem-solving skills.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/interactiveToy.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Interactive Toys">
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Socialisation Exercises</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Expose your dog to different environments, people, and other dogs in a controlled way.</li>
                    <li>Reward calm behavior and gradually introduce new experiences to reduce fear and anxiety.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/socialise.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Socialising">
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Training Place Command and Loose-lead walking -->
        <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Training “Place” Command</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Teach your dog to go to a designated spot (e.g., a mat or bed) and stay there until released.
                    </li>
                    <li>This can be a helpful command when guests arrive or in situations where you need your dog to be
                        calm and settled.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/bed.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Place Commands">
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Loose-Lead Walking</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Practice loose-lead walking by changing direction whenever your dog pulls. This helps them focus
                        on you rather than leading the walk.</li>
                    <li>Reward them when they walk by your side without pulling.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/looseLead.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Loose lead walking">
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Trick Training and Hide-and-Seek -->
        <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Trick Training</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Teach fun tricks like “roll over,” “shake,” or “spin” to engage your dog’s mind and strengthen
                        your bond.</li>
                    <li>Use clear cues and celebrate each little success to keep your dog motivated.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/cocker.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h3>Hide-and-Seek</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Hide somewhere in your home or garden and call your dog to find you. This is a fun way to
                        reinforce the recall command.</li>
                    <li>Gradually increase the difficulty by hiding in harder-to-find spots to encourage
                        problem-solving.</li>
                </ul>
                <img src="~/images/training/hide.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
            </div>
        </div>
